00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:18.410
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: What has
it been like for you?

00:01:18.410 --> 00:01:21.340
You talked about just the feelings.

00:01:21.340 --> 00:01:25.890 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Meredith Monk: Well, getting the
National Medal from President Obama,

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:27.900
I'm still shaking from it.

00:01:27.900 --> 00:01:32.770
I'll never forget it in my lifetime
and a beautiful human being,

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:37.280
and yea, I mean, really,
when they called me up,

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:39.660
I was shaking for a few hours.

00:01:39.660 --> 00:01:44.620 position:56%
It's sort of beyond your-- you know,
you just do your work, basically.

00:01:44.620 --> 00:01:47.430
So you know, something
like that happens,

00:01:47.430 --> 00:01:51.230
it's kind of beyond your
dreams or, you know?

00:01:51.230 --> 00:01:54.740
I mean, you are just step
by step doing your work.

00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:57.130
So it was a magical day.

00:01:57.130 --> 00:02:00.990
But the 50th year was really
interesting because, you know,

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:03.800
it was a way for me to also
look back over many, many,

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:06.890
many different aspects of my work.

00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:11.180
I was the Debs Composer
Residence at Carnegie Hall

00:02:11.180 --> 00:02:13.910
and so we did six concerts,
different concerts,

00:02:13.910 --> 00:02:18.210 position:56%
at Carnegie Hall really
emphasizing the variety of the work.

00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:22.340
Like for about the last
15 years I've been trying

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:25.420
to work a little bit more
with instrumental ensembles

00:02:25.420 --> 00:02:32.340 position:56%
like an orchestra or chamber groups,
mostly with voice, but you know,

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:33.830
because that is my instrument.

00:02:33.830 --> 00:02:35.130
But I did try.

00:02:35.130 --> 00:02:41.280
I did a premiere piece for a very
wonderful ensemble called the ACJW,

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:48.420
which is the Academy Carnegie
Juilliard Wild ensemble,

00:02:48.420 --> 00:02:51.250
and they get a stipend
for two years.

00:02:51.250 --> 00:02:55.320
It's young musicians who want
to play chamber music mostly,

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:58.390
and they're very, very
fine, fine musicians.

00:02:58.390 --> 00:03:00.410
So I thought, you know,
bite the bullet.

00:03:00.410 --> 00:03:02.130
Don't put a voice in there.

00:03:02.130 --> 00:03:04.220
I mean that would be the way
I would feel more secure,

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:10.310
and why don't you just use the
seven instruments and so, you know,

00:03:10.310 --> 00:03:14.330
the old days, is it my braid, is
it my-- you know the old days,

00:03:14.330 --> 00:03:18.370
when we had these things and
that was a great experience,

00:03:18.370 --> 00:03:20.550
and then I did my ensemble.

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:27.130
The last concert was a real
beautiful potpourri of music from,

00:03:27.130 --> 00:03:31.430
for 50 years, and there was a one
four hour marathon where a bunch

00:03:31.430 --> 00:03:36.160
of different musicians that I love
and that I know did their versions

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:40.180
of my music, which was very -- that
was very special including Leonardo

00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:46.590
from Sonic Youth, and you
know, DJ Spooky, Missy Mazzoli.

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:48.330
There were, you know, a
lot of different people.

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:50.010
So that was very special.

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:52.230
And then we also performed
On Behalf of Nature,

00:03:52.230 --> 00:03:59.560
which was my last large multimedia
music theater piece at BAM,

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:05.180
and that does include movement and
light, and it has eight performers

00:04:05.180 --> 00:04:12.210
in it and was basically about what
we're losing, in danger of losing.

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:15.760
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: I wish we
had the space for that here.

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:17.820
Back to your chamber
music for a moment.

00:04:17.820 --> 00:04:19.120
Do you have any plans?

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:20.650
We're in the business
of chamber music

00:04:20.650 --> 00:04:22.790
so anything we should know about?

00:04:22.790 --> 00:04:25.080
&gt;&gt; Meredith Monk: I have a piece in
mind but it probably would be more

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:29.740
for a chamber size orchestra,
maybe in voices and right now,

00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:31.310
I'm working on a new
piece with Allison

00:04:31.310 --> 00:04:33.820
and Katie called, Cellular Songs.

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:38.370 position:56%
It's right now, three -- So far I've
done four little A Cappella pieces,

00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:40.140
but it will grow from there.

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:42.630
But I'm very interested.

00:04:42.630 --> 00:04:44.890
I've always used the
voice as an instrument,

00:04:44.890 --> 00:04:49.140
and now I've been really interested
in using the instruments as voices.

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:52.660 position:56%
So I've learned a lot about that and
then it goes back into my ensemble

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:56.040
because the whole ensemble also
includes John Hollenbeck who's a

00:04:56.040 --> 00:05:00.620
fantastic multi-percussionist,
and so some of the richness

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:05.040
of the instrumental writing that I
find with working with an orchestra

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:07.900
or something like that, I can put
it right back into the ensemble.

00:05:07.900 --> 00:05:11.630 position:56%
So I think it's grown in that way
and you know, when you're an artist,

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:13.150
you just want to keep
growing and growing.

00:05:13.150 --> 00:05:18.480
That's basically my goal of
life is to hopefully be growing

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:21.940
until the day I die and be working.

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:25.990
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: I read a comment
from the critic, Tom Service,

00:05:25.990 --> 00:05:28.640
the British critic, saying
that he felt that you wanted

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:32.400
to give your listeners a vision
of concentration and attention

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:38.420
in an ever diminishing and be in
an increasing speed of the world

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:41.380
and diminishing attention circle.

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:45.560
&gt;&gt; Meredith Monk: Yes because we
are definitely victims of weapons

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:51.160
of mass distraction, which
is what Gary Snyder said,

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:52.530
and I think it's so true.

00:05:52.530 --> 00:05:56.590 position:56%
So I think that the live performance
is such a wonderful opportunity.

00:05:56.590 --> 00:06:00.300
First of all, we're all here in
the same space in the same time

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:05.010
and that's unusual and I feel
that we're losing sense of touch

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:07.890
and we're even losing the sense of
being able to look at each other

00:06:07.890 --> 00:06:10.400
in the eyes and not
have the thumbs going.

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:12.970
I always say, I think generations
from now, people are going

00:06:12.970 --> 00:06:16.080
to have hands like
this and big thumbs.

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:17.380
You know, no fingers.

00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:18.680
It's just going to be thumbs.

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:24.030
So, you know, I feel like the live
performance we're very vulnerable

00:06:24.030 --> 00:06:26.820
and that's unusual
also in the culture.

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:28.470
It's not smoothed over in any way.

00:06:28.470 --> 00:06:29.770
We could fall.

00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:31.580
We could sing the wrong note.

00:06:31.580 --> 00:06:35.280
It's like a tight rope a little
bit and it's very important

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:42.010
to affirm our human sense of touch
and connection and I think that --

00:06:42.010 --> 00:06:44.120
and then also the concentration
thing too.

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:47.350
It's not -- it's just about
being able to let go of that part

00:06:47.350 --> 00:06:51.420 position:56%
of your mind that's always
narrating your life, and now I think

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:56.310 position:56%
because of the devices of mass
distraction, we even have more irony

00:06:56.310 --> 00:07:00.130
and quotation marks and brackets
and it just goes more and more.

00:07:00.130 --> 00:07:03.120
You know, so we're looking at this,
looking at this, looking at this,

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:06.460
looking at this; how
about direct experience?

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:09.510
So I think that the live
performance has that possibility.

