00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:42.860
all kinds of things in the piece.

00:11:42.860 --> 00:11:44.660
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Yes?

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:50.730
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:11:50.730 --> 00:11:52.530
&gt;&gt; Meredith Monk: Yes.

00:11:52.530 --> 00:11:55.640
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:58.100
It's very close to what you
have to do with a Jew's harp.

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:02.150
With a Jew's harp, I change
the inside cavity of my mouth

00:12:02.150 --> 00:12:04.110
to make the different
tones that you hear

00:12:04.110 --> 00:12:06.760
over the fundamental Jew's harp.

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:12.460
So basically, I'm keeping --
it's actually not so relaxed.

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:17.110 position:56%
You have to keep that fundamental
and you close off some of the places

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:21.980
in here so that it isolates
that overtone so that midrange,

00:12:21.980 --> 00:12:23.280
you are not hearing so much.

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:26.040
You are hearing the fundamental
and then by closing off,

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:28.430
and actually it's coming
through here.

00:12:28.430 --> 00:12:32.430
You hear that overtone,
and actually, in some ways,

00:12:32.430 --> 00:12:35.310
you hear overtones
better with a men's voice

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:38.880
because you know sometimes we're
actually singing our fundamental

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:44.040
pretty high than our overtone, you
can't -- it's not human hearing.

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:46.310
I was singing that
song pretty high today

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:49.010
and so I was getting a different
kind of overtone than I might

00:12:49.010 --> 00:12:52.510
if I was singing a half a
tone lower or tone lower.

00:12:52.510 --> 00:12:55.550
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:57.350
Yes.

00:12:57.350 --> 00:13:13.050
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:13:13.050 --> 00:13:17.010
Well, first of all, my mother
was a jingle singer on the radio.

00:13:17.010 --> 00:13:19.860
She was the original Muriel Cigar,

00:13:19.860 --> 00:13:22.380
Blue Bonnet margarine,
Schaefer Beer.

00:13:22.380 --> 00:13:25.020
My grandfather was a base
baritone from Russia.

00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:28.790
And he came from the United
States and then sang in all kinds

00:13:28.790 --> 00:13:31.840
of places, Carnegie
Hall, Brooklyn Academy.

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:35.240
He would do concerts
with a contralto,

00:13:35.240 --> 00:13:36.540
base baritone and contralto.

00:13:36.540 --> 00:13:37.850
That's unusual.

00:13:37.850 --> 00:13:39.870
And then he opened
a music conservatory

00:13:39.870 --> 00:13:42.890
up in Washington Heights.

00:13:42.890 --> 00:13:45.090
So that side of the family

00:13:45.090 --> 00:13:48.460
and I heard my great
grandfather was a cantor in Russia

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:52.420
so that singing thing was something
that was very natural for me.

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:55.740
Movement was quite hard
because I have strabismus,

00:13:55.740 --> 00:13:59.650
an eye thing where I can't fuse
two images and my mother heard

00:13:59.650 --> 00:14:01.230
about Dalcroze Eurhythmics.

00:14:01.230 --> 00:14:04.290
So my earliest training was
in Dalcroze Eurhythmics,

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:07.940
which is an integration of
the body, and you learn music

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:11.840
through the body, but I think I
learned my body through music,

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:16.500
so but I was moving a lot
as a child dancing too.

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:21.890 position:56%
So I have a combined background in
music and in dance and also theater.

00:14:21.890 --> 00:14:25.880
So I think that that's also
partially why when I had

00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:30.080
that revelation at the piano
doing regular classical exercises

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:33.790
that I realized, the voice can
also be a nonverbal instrument.

00:14:33.790 --> 00:14:37.130
I think coming from a movement
background, I trusted that.

00:14:37.130 --> 00:14:40.820
I trusted that nonverbal
communication is very deep,

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:43.600 position:56%
and at Sarel [assumed spelling]
Arts, I was in the voice department.

00:14:43.600 --> 00:14:49.880 position:56%
I studied classical singing leader,
opera workshop, and then when I came

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:54.840 position:56%
to New York, my pieces were more
gesture based; a little bit of voice

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:57.730
and very cinematic
kind of structures,

00:14:57.730 --> 00:14:59.030
and I was missing singing.

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:01.810
And so I just sat down at the
piano and started vocalizing,

00:15:01.810 --> 00:15:05.560
and I had this revelation
and from that point on,

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:09.340
my life really changed, and
the revelation also included

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:13.270
that within the voice could be male
and female, different landscapes,

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:17.870
characters, ages, different
ways of producing sound.

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:19.170
I felt that it was a very --

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:22.810
I instinctively felt that it was a
very deep and ancient instrument.

00:15:22.810 --> 00:15:27.420
It could delineate feelings
and shades of feelings

00:15:27.420 --> 00:15:29.630
for which we don't have words.

00:15:29.630 --> 00:15:34.250
And it also, strangely enough, was
a way of coming back to my family

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:37.380
because being in a bunch
of singer family, you know,

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:42.380 position:56%
a family with a bunch of singers,
it's kind of hard to find your spot.

00:15:42.380 --> 00:15:44.990
So and I had done a lot of
choreography at that point

00:15:44.990 --> 00:15:47.790
and I had -- because of
my physical limitations,

00:15:47.790 --> 00:15:52.530
I had to find my own vocabulary
which was a blessing, you know,

00:15:52.530 --> 00:15:58.050
that I found my own way of finding
movement so I knew how to work

00:15:58.050 --> 00:16:00.130
so that when I had the
revelation with the voice,

00:16:00.130 --> 00:16:03.490
I knew to go into the studio and
I knew how to work with my voice

00:16:03.490 --> 00:16:07.890
and I had a more wide range,
you know, you could say,

00:16:07.890 --> 00:16:11.170
virtuosic instrument as a singer.

00:16:11.170 --> 00:16:14.990
So it was like I came home
when I had that revelation

00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:18.490
and it's been all these years
thinking of the voice and the body

00:16:18.490 --> 00:16:24.760
as one, because I think that our
singing style is very kinetic.

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:27.980
And then like Katie didn't
come from a movement background

00:16:27.980 --> 00:16:31.010
but she's a wonderful
mover so you know, it's --

00:16:31.010 --> 00:16:35.390
we come from different
backgrounds with the ensemble.

00:16:35.390 --> 00:16:37.890
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Maybe just
one or two more questions.

00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:41.020
Maybe here.

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:43.560 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I think there's a lot of interest

00:16:43.560 --> 00:16:50.130
in the way you produce different
sounds, but I was curious

00:16:50.130 --> 00:16:54.860
about one aspect of it as
to learning how to do that

00:16:54.860 --> 00:17:00.110 position:56%
or spending time alone in New Mexico
or wherever, your way you do that,

00:17:00.110 --> 00:17:06.170
about the evolution of your ability
to make this a different sound.

00:17:06.170 --> 00:17:11.730
How does that work for you and are
you able to hear yourself working

00:17:11.730 --> 00:17:17.390
or do you have to take that
out and teach yourself?

00:17:17.390 --> 00:17:18.690
&gt;&gt; Meredith Monk: It's
very interesting.

00:17:18.690 --> 00:17:21.800
Oh, well there's actually two or
three different questions in there.

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:23.800
One is the listening, which is --

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:28.090 position:56%
I mean in a way, the older I get the
more I realize that I actually live

00:17:28.090 --> 00:17:34.260 position:56%
through my ears and I've just been
more and more just enjoying sitting,

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:35.910
especially when I'm in New Mexico

00:17:35.910 --> 00:17:38.870
because I don't have traffic
and everything going by.

00:17:38.870 --> 00:17:41.570
Sometimes I just sit like
I feel like I'm like a dog.

00:17:41.570 --> 00:17:42.870
I'm like --

00:17:42.870 --> 00:17:44.170
[ Laughter ]

00:17:44.170 --> 00:17:47.400
You know how dogs just sit there?

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:53.490 position:56%
And I just listen and you know, I've
always been more a doer than a be-er

00:17:53.490 --> 00:17:55.270
so I'm learning how to be.

00:17:55.270 --> 00:17:58.820
I also have meditation practice,
which is helping me learn how to be

00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:02.730
but I just sit there and
listen and I'm just so stunned

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:08.350
by the cosmic conductor, you know,
in nature, how sounds come and go,

00:18:08.350 --> 00:18:11.100
and I guess I've always
felt very close to that.

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:14.330
And then as far as hearing
myself, I mean I do hear myself.

00:18:14.330 --> 00:18:18.590
I don't have to go outside to teach
it to someone else and hear it.

00:18:18.590 --> 00:18:23.270
I do tape myself, you know,
or notate what I'm doing.

00:18:23.270 --> 00:18:26.210
But it's a funny question that
you would ask because I think

00:18:26.210 --> 00:18:30.960 position:56%
at certain times in all of our lives
as singers, there's a certain point

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:36.390
where you have to kind of
relearn that coordination

00:18:36.390 --> 00:18:40.640
of hearing yourself in
relation to what's around you.

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:43.710
You know, sometimes you
lose that coordination

00:18:43.710 --> 00:18:46.910 position:56%
so you are either not hearing what's
around you enough or you are hearing

00:18:46.910 --> 00:18:50.790
or you are not hearing yourself
enough so really the, you know,

00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:54.900 position:56%
staying in tune and everything is
doing both simultaneously; listening

00:18:54.900 --> 00:18:57.380
and being able to hear yourself.

00:18:57.380 --> 00:19:00.430
So sometimes, I give in my
workshop like an exercise

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:01.730
like that where you are singing.

00:19:01.730 --> 00:19:04.300
It's like the big group of
people and you choose a tone

00:19:04.300 --> 00:19:05.600
and everybody chooses a tone.

00:19:05.600 --> 00:19:09.150
At the same time, you are
listening to the whole thing,

00:19:09.150 --> 00:19:12.870
and you choose somebody else's
tone when you finish yours

00:19:12.870 --> 00:19:17.980 position:56%
so that it keeps on shifting, you
know it's kind of like a big cluster

00:19:17.980 --> 00:19:21.190 position:56%
that keeps on shifting and so that's
that thing of being able to --

00:19:21.190 --> 00:19:25.460
and also when you sing with groups,
like say choral pieces or something

00:19:25.460 --> 00:19:28.290
like that or groups, I always
say if you only hear yourself,

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:31.440
you are singing too loud because
one of the most wonderful things

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:34.360
about singing with other people
is hearing the other people.

00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:36.910
That's a pleasure of it.

